vim editor ---------------------

	usage: vim test.txt (filename) // this open file in vim if test.txt not exist then vim 						  						  create test.txt
	Now, vim have multiple modes 3 basic modes:
		1-> Normal - Default; for navigation and simple editing // default it is in normal 										   mode or press escape to 										   enter in normal mode.

		2-> Insert - For explicitly inserting and modifying text // press i to enter 										    insert mode

		3-> command Line - For operations like saving, exiting, etc. // press : followed 											by command to 											execute command.

		commands:
			1-> :q! or :ZQ - to quit vim without saving anything.

			2-> :wq or :x! - to save file and quit vim.

			3-> :set number - display line number

			4-> :<line number > - jump curson to that line number

			5-> :$ - jump to the end line of the file.

			6-> dd - this command delete line where cursor is present.

			7-> u - this command undo the changes in file 

			8-> ctrl+r - this command redo the changes in the file

			9-> v - enter the visual mode where using right left up down key to select and deselect lines in file

			10-> y (yank mode)- it copy the selected lines in file in clipboard 			
			11-> o - create new line underneath a line where cursor is present and 	enter in to insert mode.

			12-> esc - to enter normal mode 

			13-> p - paste the line in clipboard.
